<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>Does the Bible give absolute proof that our spirit can only be saved before we experience mortal death?  I'm not finding it<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END-->  <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->   OK, this one I might give you a hard time about.  A lot of our argument in the past where about that idea about what the Bible says and doesn't and you were on the flip side of that one! <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->   Ok, hard time over.<br>
<br>
No, I don't believe I can.  My saying that 'what ifs' might change the way you view Jesus' death had to do more along the lines of where it took you theologically.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>Yes, but he also hasn't come up to face the second death yet which does not come until after this world has passed away and all face the final judgment. <hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END-->  True, but it would seem that he's being punished in hell (or even purgatory if you'd like <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :p --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/images/emoticons/tongue.gif ALT=":p"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->  ) so what you're saying is that at the end of time after being punished he'll get an opportunity to change his mind?  Why not right then and there? <br>
<br>
The ideas you're struggling with (and it's ok to struggle with ideas.  In fact it should be mandatory) are giving you conclusions (ie that we get a second chance after death) that aren't spelled out in the Bible and also have never to my knowledge been taught in the 2000 years of Christianity.  Just something to consider.  And I say that not in a mean way but in the gentle loving way.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>I'm not following you<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--> - I mean that there are many things that over time I have struggled with.  Suffering is one I still continue to struggle with.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>And if we look at history, just look at the Old Testament, we see how God made His physical presence known and still the Jews set themselves against Him.  ....   I think there are many who would chose Him if, like Thomas, they received the physical proof they needed <!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr> And I think that even our experience on PC with the antheists that there will always be people where any amount of proof will not be enough.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>I don't know, I wish I had a<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--> AMEN sister!  Don't we all.  Of course I know a Church that has been asking questions and struggling with ideas and formulating answers for about 2000 years now. <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :char --><img src=http://heartjoys.fcpages.com/Sparrow'sHearth/char006.gif ALT=":char"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->   <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START ;) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/images/emoticons/wink.gif ALT=";)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <br>
